{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-953f668215363771", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t\n2\t\n3\tFdAudio: MeanFlow-Anchored Fréchet-Distance Post-Training for One-Step Text-to-Audio Generation\n4\t\n5\t Report GitHub Issue\n6\t\n7\t ×\n8\t\n9\t Title:\n10\t\n11\t Content selection saved. Describe the issue below:\n12\t\n13\t Description:\n14\t\n15\t Submit without GitHub\n16\t Submit in GitHub\n17\t\n18\t arXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\n19\t Learn more\n20\t ×\n21\t\n22\t Back to arXiv\n23\t\n24\t Why HTML?\n25\t\n26\t Report Issue\n27\t\n28\t Back to Abstract\n29\t\n30\t Download PDF\n31\t\n32\tAbstract\n33\t\n34\tI Introduction\n35\t\n36\tII Related Work\n37\t\n38\tII-A Few-step T2A generation\n39\t\n40\tII-B MeanFlow one-step generation\n41\t\n42\tIII Method\n43\t\n44\tIII-A Fréchet-distance post-training\n45\t\n46\tIII-B MeanFlow anchor for multi-step preservation\n47\t\n48\tIV Experimental Setup\n49\t\n50\tIV-A Data\n51\t\n52\tIV-B Metrics\n53\t\n54\tIV-C Training\n55\t\n56\tV Results\n57\t\n58\tV-A System-level comparisons\n59\t\n60\tV-B MeanFlow anchor\n61\t\n62\tV-C Encoders for multi-representation FD-loss\n63\t\n64\tVI Conclusion\n65\t\n66\tReferences\n67\t\n68\t License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0\n69\t\n70\tarXiv:2607.10421v1 [eess.AS] 11 Jul 2026\n71\t\n72\tFdAudio: MeanFlow-Anchored Fréchet-Distance Post-Training for One-Step Text-to-Audio Generation\n73\t\n74\tKuan-Po Huang⋆, Bo-Ru Lu†, Ho-Lam Chung⋆, Shih-Hsin Wang⋆, Hung-yi Lee⋆\n75\t†This work is unrelated to the author’s position at Amazon.\n76\t\n77\tAbstract\n78\t\n79\tWhile recent few-step sampling text-to-audio generation models like MeanAudio substantially accelerate generation by modeling average velocities, their strict one-step generation quality still lags significantly behind multi-step counterparts.\n80\tWe propose FdAudio to bridge this gap. Unlike MeanAudio, which relies solely on regression against target velocity fields, our post-training approach optimizes the final one-step distribution directly across pre-trained embedding spaces via a multi-representation Fréchet-distance (FD) loss. Crucially, to prevent the multi-step degradation that naive post-training with FD-loss causes, we introduce a MeanFlow consistency objective as a structural anchor.\n81\tResults demonstrate that FdAudio establishes state-of-the-art one-step T2A generation quality among few-step systems, yielding an 11.4% reduction in FD score and a 28.8% improvement in FAD score relative to the baseline MeanAudio framework. Notably, we solve FD post-training’s naive multi-step degradation issue by proposing the MeanFlow anchor, enabling a 25-step sampling path to maintain high-fidelity audio synthesis that matches or surpasses strong multi-step models at a fraction of their computational latency.\n82\t\n83\tI Introduction\n84\t\n85\tText-to-audio (T2A) aims to automate the process by synthesizing general sound, from ambient scenes to sound events, directly from a natural language prompt, with applications across games, film, and digital content creation. Because inference is performed far more frequently than training in these practical applications, the inference cost becomes a central concern [30]. However, state-of-the-art systems are mostly built on diffusion [9] and flow-matching [22] models [23, 11, 27, 15, 13, 39, 6, 20], which produce high-fidelity audio through an iterative sampling process. The model is evaluated sequentially over tens to hundreds of timesteps, at each time step taking a partially denoised latent and predicting a small update that gradually recovers the final clean audio latents. This sequential loop is the primary source of their high inference latency.\n86\t\n87\tTo remove this bottleneck, recent systems distill or shorten the sampling trajectory for few- or one-step inference, including\n88\tConsistencyTTA [1], AudioLCM [24],\n89\tAudioTurbo [40], SoundCTM [32], AudioDEAR [12], and\n90\tMeanAudio [21]. Although dramatically faster, these few-step models still trail their multi-step counterparts in generation quality. This motivates the central question of our work: can we substantially improve the generation quality of one-step audio generation?\n91\t\n92\tA recent promising direction in the image generation domain is to apply Fréchet-distance (FD) post-training [38] to finetune a pretrained one-step generator [26, 5] so that the distribution of its one-step outputs matches real data in the feature spaces of pretrained representation extractors [35, 25, 7, 29, 36, 31]. This approach is appealing because it is simple and direct: it only requires precomputed real-data statistics, without teacher distillation, adversarial training, or per-sample regression targets.\n93\t\n94\tWe adapt this recipe to audio by computing the FD-loss over pretrained audio encoders, including PANNs [18], PaSST [19], BEATs [2], and AudioMAE [14]. While this substantially improves one-step audio quality, we find that it severely harms multi-step sampling. For example, as shown in the results of Section V-B, a model post-trained with FD-loss achieves a strong one-step FAD of 1.27, but its FAD nearly triples to 3.61 when sampled with 25 steps. This suggests that FD post-training, when applied alone, encourages the model to optimize only the final one-step output. As a result, the model bypasses the iterative flow-matching trajectory and collapses the continuous denoising path into a direct noise-to-data mapping, making multi-step sampling less effective.\n95\tWhile strong one-step performance is highly desirable for real-time applications, discarding the multi-step trajectory restricts deployment flexibility.\n96\t\n97\tTo prevent this collapse, post-training must preserve the model’s denoising trajectory rather than only improving its one-step output. Therefore, we introduce the MeanFlow consistency objective [4], which mitigates the collapse issue. By regularizing the average velocity over arbitrary sub-intervals [r,t][r,t], MeanFlow helps preserve the property that the same model can be sampled with either one or multiple steps. This is precisely the property that naive FD post-training destroys.\n98\t\n99\tOur use of MeanFlow is different from prior work. MeanFlow [4] and its audio instantiation MeanAudio [21] use MeanFlow as the primary training objective for learning fast one-step generators. In contrast, our goal is to leverage the benefits of FD post-training without sacrificing multi-step sampling. We therefore use the FD-loss to improve the one-step output distribution, while repurposing MeanFlow as a lightweight regularizer that preserves the underlying sampling trajectory and prevents the model from collapsing into a purely one-step mapping.\n100\t\n101\tBuilding on this, we propose FdAudio111Demo: https://fdoneaudio.github.io/222Code: https://github.com/nobel861017/FdAudio.\n102\tFdAudio combines FD post-training with MeanFlow regularization: the FD-loss improves one-step generation quality, while the MeanFlow term preserves the velocity field needed for high-quality multi-step sampling.\n103\t\n104\tOur contributions are:\n105\t\n106\t• \n107\t\n108\tWe identify a fundamental conflict between distribution-level post-training and trajectory-based generation: optimizing the FD-loss sharpens one-step output but overwrites the velocity field, so the generator can no longer sample across multiple steps.\n109\t\n110\t• \n111\t\n112\tWe resolve this conflict with a MeanFlow consistency anchor: a single set of weights that generates high-quality audio in one step and still samples well with many steps without separate models or retraining.\n113\t\n114\t• \n115\t\n116\tAt only 120M parameters, FdAudio reaches state-of-the-art one-step T2A generation on AudioCaps among several few-step models, while matching or surpassing other strong multi-step systems.\n117\t\n118\tII Related Work\n119\t\n120\tII-A Few-step T2A generation\n121\t\n122\tWhile several diffusion- or flow-matching-based T2A models [23, 11, 27, 15, 13, 39, 6] synthesize high-quality audio, their iterative sampling processes during inference incur high computational costs and substantial latency.\n123\tFormally, given a conditioning text prompt cc and an initial noise sample xT∼𝒩​(0,I)x_{T}\\sim\\mathcal{N}(0,I), the standard inference process requires evaluating a parameterized model FF over TT discrete timesteps. The sampling trajectory produces a sequence of intermediate states xT,xT−1,…,x0x_{T},x_{T-1},\\dots,x_{0}, where each update step is defined as:\n124\t\n125\txt−1=Φ​(xt,F​(xt,t,c)),t=T,T−1,…,1x_{t-1}=\\Phi(x_{t},F(x_{t},t,c)),\\quad t=T,T-1,\\dots,1\n126\t\n127\t(1)\n128\t\n129\twhere Φ\\Phi denotes the numerical solver or discrete sampling algorithm. The final synthesized audio output is the terminal state x0=xx_{0}=x. Because TT typically ranges from tens to hundreds, this sequential evaluation loop acts as a fundamental bottleneck.\n130\tThis limitation has driven the development of few-step generation techniques. For instance, ConsistencyTTA [1] and AudioLCM [24] apply consistency distillation [34] to achieve few-step generation, however, the performance of their one-step generation still significantly lags behind state-of-the-art multi-step T2A models.\n131\tMore recently, MeanAudio [21] instantiated the aforementioned MeanFlow framework for text-to-audio generation, demonstrating that this alternative training objective can yield relatively better one-step audio quality, though it still falls short of its multi-step counterpart. In this work, we aim to close this quality gap, establishing state-of-the-art performance for one-step T2A generation.\n132\t\n133\tII-B MeanFlow one-step generation\n134\t\n135\tTo overcome the high inference latency of traditional iterative sampling, the MeanFlow framework [4] is designed to directly learn the average velocity of a generation trajectory over an arbitrary time interval. While standard flow-matching models approximate the instantaneous velocity and therefore require extensive numerical integration across many timesteps, MeanFlow structurally bypasses this bottleneck to enable high-fidelity sampling in a single or very few network evaluations.\n136\t\n137\tMechanically, this framework operates within the latent space of a pretrained autoencoder. Let xx denote a clean data latent representation and let ϵ∼𝒩​(0,I)\\epsilon\\sim\\mathcal{N}(0,I) represent a noise sample. Standard flow-matching formulates a linear interpolant as zt=(1−t)​x+t​ϵz_{t}=(1-t)x+t\\epsilon for time t∈[0,1]t\\in[0,1], where z0=xz_{0}=x represents the true data distribution and z1=ϵz_{1}=\\epsilon represents the pure noise distribution. The instantaneous velocity along this path is defined as v=z˙t=ϵ−xv=\\dot{z}_{t}=\\epsilon-x.\n138\t\n139\tInstead of predicting vv, the MeanFlow objective targets the average velocity, denoted as uθ​(zt,r,t)u_{\\theta}(z_{t},r,t), over a specific interval [r,t][r,t]. This average velocity is formally defined as u​(zt,r,t)=1t−r​∫rtv​(zτ,τ)​𝑑τu(z_{t},r,t)=\\frac{1}{t-r}\\int_{r}^{t}v(z_{\\tau},\\tau)d\\tau. Differentiating this definition with respect to tt yields the fundamental MeanFlow identity:\n140\t\n141\tu​(zt,r,t)=v​(zt,t)−(t−r)​dd​t​u​(zt,r,t),u(z_{t},r,t)=v(z_{t},t)-(t-r)\\frac{d}{dt}u(z_{t},r,t),\n142\t\n143\t(2)\n144\t\n145\twhere dd​t​u\\frac{d}{dt}u represents the total derivative along the trajectory, computed via a Jacobian-vector product (JVP). Model optimization is performed by regressing the parameterized function uθu_{\\theta} onto the right-hand side of this identity, applying a stop-gradient operation (sg\\mathrm{sg}) to the target:\n146\t\n147\tℒMF=∥uθ​(zt,r,t)−sg​[v^−(t−r)​dd​t​uθ]∥a2,\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{MF}}=\\big\\lVert u_{\\theta}(z_{t},r,t)-\\mathrm{sg}\\left[\\hat{v}-(t-r)\\frac{d}{dt}u_{\\theta}\\right]\\big\\rVert^{2}_{\\mathrm{a}},\n148\t\n149\t(3)\n150\t\n151\twhere ∥⋅∥a\\lVert\\cdot\\rVert_{\\mathrm{a}} denotes the adaptive ℓ2\\ell_{2} loss introduced in [4], and v^\\hat{v} incorporates classifier-free guidance [10] into the velocity target.\n152\tFollowing training, a final sample can be generated utilizing a sampling step: x^=ϵ−uθ​(ϵ,0,1)\\hat{x}=\\epsilon-u_{\\theta}(\\epsilon,0,1).\n153\tMore generally, generation can be executed in nn steps by integrating uθu_{\\theta} over a partition of the interval [0,1][0,1].\n154\t\n155\tMeanAudio [21], a model utilizing the MeanFlow objective [4], achieves relatively better one-step audio generation quality compared to previous few-step sampling models [12, 40, 1, 24], but still falls significantly behind its multi-step counterpart. In this work, we aim at reaching state-of-the-art performance for one-step T2A generation while closing the quality gap between one-step and multi-step sampling models.\n156\t\n157\tIII Method\n158\t\n159\tOur goal is high-quality one-step T2A generation that keeps the inference efficiency of single-step sampling without giving up the option of multi-step sampling. We build on Fréchet-distance (FD) post-training, which Section III-A formalizes together with its multi-representation form. As discussed there, FD post-training is an effective one-step objective but overwrites the model’s learned velocity field, so the post-trained model can no longer sample well across multiple steps. To support both one- and multi-step sampling, Section III-B adds a MeanFlow consistency term that anchors the FD distribution matching while preserving the multi-step trajectory.\n160\t\n161\tIII-A Fréchet-distance post-training\n162\t\n163\tFréchet-distance (FD).\n164\tTo evaluate how closely a generative model replicates real-world data, models are often compared at a distribution level within a fixed representation space. Let ψ​(⋅)\\psi(\\cdot) represent a pretrained, frozen representation extractor. We map a collection of reference target audio clips, 𝒜gt={ai}\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{gt}}=\\{a_{i}\\}, and a corresponding set of generated audio samples, 𝒜g={a^i}\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{g}}=\\{\\hat{a}_{i}\\}, through this extractor to obtain their latent vectors. Assuming these embeddings follow multivariate normal distributions, we compute their empirical first and second moments:\n165\t\n166\tμgt=𝔼​[ψ​(a)],Σgt=Cov​[ψ​(a)]\\mu_{\\text{gt}}=\\mathbb{E}[\\psi(a)],\\quad\\Sigma_{\\text{gt}}=\\text{Cov}[\\psi(a)]\n167\t\n168\t(4)\n169\t\n170\tμg=𝔼​[ψ​(a^)],Σg=Cov​[ψ​(a^)]\\mu_{\\text{g}}=\\mathbb{E}[\\psi(\\hat{a})],\\quad\\Sigma_{\\text{g}}=\\text{Cov}[\\psi(\\hat{a})]\n171\t\n172\t(5)\n173\t\n174\tThe structural discrepancy between these two continuous domains is quantified using the Wasserstein-2 distance, expressed here as the Fréchet metric:\n175\t\n176\tF​Dψ​(𝒜gt,𝒜g)=‖μgt−μg‖22+Tr​(Σgt+Σg−2​(Σgt​Σg)12)FD_{\\psi}(\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{gt}},\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{g}})=\\|\\mu_{\\text{gt}}-\\mu_{\\text{g}}\\|_{2}^{2}+\\text{Tr}\\big(\\Sigma_{\\text{gt}}+\\Sigma_{\\text{g}}-2(\\Sigma_{\\text{gt}}\\Sigma_{\\text{g}})^{\\frac{1}{2}}\\big)\n177\t\n178\t(6)\n179\t\n180\tWhen ψ\\psi is instantiated as the VGGish architecture [8], this metric resolves to the standard Fréchet Audio Distance (FAD) [16].\n181\t\n182\tFigure 1: Overview of the post-training framework for FdAudio. (a) FD-Loss calculation pipeline: Ground truth audio statistics (μg​t\\mu_{gt}, Σg​t\\Sigma_{gt}) are precomputed prior to training. During the optimization step, a one-step forward pass synthesizes a generated sample a^\\hat{a}. This sample is processed through frozen, pretrained encoders (ψ\\psi) to compute and maintain the generated statistics (μg\\mu_{g}, Σg\\Sigma_{g}) via a queue-based estimator. (b) MeanFlow Anchor: To prevent the multi-step collapse associated with naive FD post-training, the framework computes the MeanFlow consistency loss (ℒM​F\\mathcal{L}_{MF}) over uniformly sampled intermediate timesteps (r<t∈[0,1]r<t\\in[0,1]), preserving the continuous sampling trajectory for high-fidelity multi-step generation. \n183\t\n184\tFD-loss.\n185\tSince FD quantifies the distribution-wise discrepancy between generated audio (𝒜g\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{g}}) and ground-truth audio (𝒜gt\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{gt}}), it serves as a natural and direct training objective for generation tasks, denoted as ℒF​D\\mathcal{L}_{FD} in Eq. (7).\n186\t\n187\tℒF​D=F​Dψ​(𝒜gt,𝒜g)\\mathcal{L}_{FD}=FD_{\\psi}(\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{gt}},\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{g}})\n188\t\n189\t(7)\n190\t\n191\tHowever, treating this evaluation metric as an explicit optimization loss presents major computational problems. Computing a reliable, full-rank covariance matrix demands tracking thousands of generated instances across the training trajectory. Backpropagating gradients through such a large population pool at every training iteration is computationally prohibitive, while attempting to estimate these moments over small training mini-batches introduces extreme statistical variance that destabilizes the training process. To bypass these limitations for FD estimation, [38] proposed a queue-based estimator by using a queue that caches the representation vectors of the NN most recently synthesized audio clips. At each optimization step, the representations extracted from the active batch push out the oldest BB elements in the queue. The empirical mean and covariance are then evaluated over the entire active queue. Crucially, elements inherited from prior iterations are detached from the computational graph, enforcing that gradients flow only through the vectors belonging to the current batch.\n192\t\n193\tMulti-representation FD-loss.\n194\tRelying exclusively on a single feature extractor may fail to capture the full spectrum of perceptual audio characteristics. The FD-loss framework can be naturally extended to optimize the generator across a diverse ensemble of JJ independent representation spaces, denoted as {ψj}j=1J\\{\\psi_{j}\\}_{j=1}^{J}. A practical challenge in this joint optimization is that the raw Fréchet Distances computed in different embedding spaces often vary by several orders of magnitude. A naive summation would cause the representations with naturally larger numerical scales to disproportionately dominate the learning signal. To ensure stable and balanced optimization, we dynamically normalize each representation’s contribution to a unit scale. This is achieved by dividing each loss term by its stop-gradiented current value, accompanied by a small stability constant cc:\n195\t\n196\tℒMulti-FD=∑j=1Jwj​F​Dψj​(𝒜gt,𝒜g)sg​(F​Dψj​(𝒜gt,𝒜g))+c\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{Multi-FD}}=\\sum_{j=1}^{J}w_{j}\\frac{FD_{\\psi_{j}}(\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{gt}},\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{g}})}{\\text{sg}\\big(FD_{\\psi_{j}}(\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{gt}},\\mathcal{A}_{\\text{g}})\\big)+c}\n197\t\n198\t(8)\n199\t\n200\twhere wjw_{j} designates the specific weighting factor for the jj-th representation space. This dynamic scaling standardizes the gradient magnitudes across all representation domains.\n201\t\n202\tWhile FD-loss successfully aligns the generated distribution with the target manifold, it inherently forces the model into a single-step generation paradigm. During post-training, the generated sample x^\\hat{x} must be synthesized via a single sampling step directly from noise, bypassing the iterative numerical solver. Attempting to optimize FD-loss on outputs generated via multiple sampling steps is impractical; backpropagating gradients through a fully unrolled TT-step generation trajectory requires caching intermediate network activations across all steps, vastly exceeding standard hardware memory limits. Consequently, the optimization of FD post-training updates the network weights to map pure noise directly to the clean data distribution in a single forward pass, overwriting the model’s originally learned progressive velocity field. This fundamentally reshapes the model from a continuous flow integrator into a rigid, one-step distribution mapper, resulting in severe audio degradation if the post-trained model is subsequently evaluated using a multi-step sampling process.\n203\t\n204\tIII-B MeanFlow anchor for multi-step preservation\n205\t\n206\tTo resolve the multi-step collapse induced by standard FD post-training, the optimization process must be constrained so that the model cannot simply discard its learned velocity field in favor of a rigid, one-step mapping. To achieve this, as illustrated in Fig. 1 (b), we propose anchoring the FD distribution-matching process with the MeanFlow [4] objective.\n207\t\n208\tWhile the FD-loss evaluates the model at the terminal timestep to pull the one-step output towards the real data manifold, the MeanFlow objective ℒMF\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{MF}} in Eq. (3) explicitly enforces trajectory consistency across arbitrary sub-intervals [r,t][r,t]. By jointly optimizing these two objectives, the MeanFlow loss acts as a powerful regularizer. It forces the network to ensure that its predictions remain valid average velocities that can be numerically integrated, even as the FD-loss reshapes the global distribution of the terminal state.\n209\t\n210\tFormally, during the post-training phase, the network parameters θ\\theta are updated by minimizing a joint objective function that combines the single-step distributional alignment with the continuous trajectory constraint:\n211\t\n212\tℒtotal=ℒMulti-FD+λ​ℒMF\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{total}}=\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{\\text{Multi-FD}}}+\\lambda\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{MF}}\n213\t\n214\t(9)\n215\t\n216\twhere λ\\lambda is a balancing hyperparameter.\n217\t\n218\tIn practice, at each training iteration, the optimization is decoupled into two computational streams. First, the model calculates the MeanFlow loss ℒMF\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{MF}} over uniformly sampled intermediate timesteps r<t∼𝒰​(0,1)r<t\\sim\\mathcal{U}(0,1) to maintain the integrity of the progressive denoising path. Second, the model evaluates a separate one-step forward pass directly from noise to data (r=0,t=1r=0,t=1) to compute the generated sample a^\\hat{a} required for the FD-loss calculation. This dual-stream approach guarantees that the model simultaneously learns to produce one-step audio generation via FD-loss, while fundamentally preserving its identity as a continuous flow integrator capable of high-fidelity multi-step sampling.\n219\t\n220\tIV Experimental Setup\n221\t\n222\tIV-A Data\n223\t\n224\tThe training data we used is an aggregation of AudioCaps [17] and WavCaps [28], resulting in a total of 387,438 audio samples. Due to budget restrictions, we only sampled 80,000 samples randomly and trained each model for one epoch.\n225\tEvaluation is conducted on the AudioCaps test set 10-second clips.\n226\t\n227\tIV-B Metrics\n228\t\n229\tSeveral key objective and subjective metrics are used to evaluate the performance of the synthesized audio. To measure fidelity at the distribution level, we include two metrics: FDPANN\\text{FD}_{\\text{PANN}} and FAD [16]. Both metrics calculate the Fréchet Distance via Eq. (6), but utilize different backbone representation extractors. In this work, FDPANN\\text{FD}_{\\text{PANN}} leverages PANNs [18] (denoted as FD), whereas FAD employs VGGish [8].\n230\tWe also include the Kullback–Leibler (KL) divergence and the Inception Score (IS; [33]) to evaluate the distribution of sound events and overall generation diversity. To measure how well a T2A model follows the semantic content of a natural language prompt, we report the CLAP score [37]333CLAP model: music_speech_audioset_epoch_15_esc_89.98.pt.. To assess human perceptual quality, we conduct subjective listening tests to gather Mean Opinion Scores. Specifically, 9 raters evaluated a total of 90 generated audio samples. These include REL to evaluate text-relevance, indicating how faithfully the audio aligns with the prompt, and OVL to measure overall audio quality.\n231\tTo measure the inference speed of T2A models, we follow IMPACT [13] by reporting the time to generate eight 10-second audio clips on an NVIDIA V100 32GB RAM GPU.\n232\t\n233\tTABLE I: System-level performance of T2A generation models on AudioCaps.\n234\t“Step” is the number of sampling steps;\n235\tLatency is the time to generate a batch of 8 clips on an Nvidia V100 32GB.\n236\tBest values among few-step methods are bold, second-best underlined.\n237\t\n238\tAudioCaps\n239\t\n240\t# para\n241\t\n242\tStep\n243\t\n244\tFD↓\\downarrow\n245\t\n246\tFAD ↓\\downarrow\n247\t\n248\tKL↓\\downarrow\n249\t\n250\tIS↑\\uparrow\n251\t\n252\tCLAP↑\\uparrow\n253\t\n254\tLatency↓\\downarrow\n255\t\n256\tGround Truth\n257\t\n258\t-\n259\t\n260\t-\n261\t\n262\t-\n263\t\n264\t-\n265\t\n266\t-\n267\t\n268\t-\n269\t\n270\t0.412\n271\t\n272\t-\n273\t\n274\tMulti-step Sampling\n275\t\n276\tTango 2\n277\t\n278\t866M\n279\t\n280\t200\n281\t\n282\t17.60\n283\t\n284\t2.82\n285\t\n286\t1.18\n287\t\n288\t10.12\n289\t\n290\t0.328\n291\t\n292\t182.23\n293\t\n294\tTangoFlux\n295\t\n296\t516M\n297\t\n298\t50\n299\t\n300\t19.69\n301\t\n302\t2.31\n303\t\n304\t1.19\n305\t\n306\t12.35\n307\t\n308\t0.318\n309\t\n310\t45.50\n311\t\n312\tEzAudio-XL (24kHz)\n313\t\n314\t874M\n315\t\n316\t50\n317\t\n318\t13.94\n319\t\n320\t3.30\n321\t\n322\t1.27\n323\t\n324\t11.37\n325\t\n326\t0.314\n327\t\n328\t39.78\n329\t\n330\tMake-an-Audio 2\n331\t\n332\t160M\n333\t\n334\t100\n335\t\n336\t14.76\n337\t\n338\t1.21\n339\t\n340\t1.27\n341\t\n342\t9.99\n343\t\n344\t0.282\n345\t\n346\t15.87\n347\t\n348\tAudioLDM2-L\n349\t\n350\t712M\n351\t\n352\t200\n353\t\n354\t24.20\n355\t\n356\t2.10\n357\t\n358\t1.54\n359\t\n360\t8.31\n361\t\n362\t0.232\n363\t\n364\t194.77\n365\t\n366\tAudioMNTP\n367\t\n368\t193M\n369\t\n370\t100\n371\t\n372\t14.81\n373\t\n374\t1.68\n375\t\n376\t1.16\n377\t\n378\t9.67\n379\t\n380\t-\n381\t\n382\t-\n383\t\n384\tIMPACT\n385\t\n386\t193M\n387\t\n388\t100\n389\t\n390\t15.25\n391\t\n392\t1.26\n393\t\n394\t1.06\n395\t\n396\t10.57\n397\t\n398\t-\n399\t\n400\t22.34\n401\t\n402\tResonate-GRPO (44kHz)\n403\t\n404\t468M\n405\t\